WEBVTT

00:08.760 --> 00:12.840
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.540 --> 00:34.040
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.980 --> 00:38.500
And here are your hosts.

00:43.640 --> 00:44.840
This is David Cruz.

00:45.100 --> 00:45.700
And Daryl Lane.

00:46.340 --> 00:48.220
How and when did science fiction begin?

00:48.860 --> 00:50.540
Well, that's a question with numerous answers.

00:50.980 --> 00:54.460
And one major problem in answering it is that science fiction has not always been a separate

00:54.460 --> 00:55.400
category of fiction.

00:56.060 --> 00:59.380
Its disengagement from so-called mainstream literature is fairly recent.

00:59.860 --> 01:02.080
Writer Elle Sprague de Camp has some thoughts on the subject.

01:03.000 --> 01:10.200
You have to remember that at one time, imaginative fiction, that is science fiction and fantasy,

01:10.360 --> 01:11.600
was the mainstream.

01:12.540 --> 01:21.300
Prior to, I think it was about the year 1719, when Defoe published Robinson Crusoe, there

01:21.300 --> 01:26.040
was, practically speaking, no such thing as realistic fiction.

01:26.820 --> 01:32.080
There were one or two scattered exceptions, but like the first one was Don Quixote.

01:33.140 --> 01:39.340
But by and large, practically all fiction had elements that we should recognize today

01:39.340 --> 01:40.720
as science fiction or fantasy.

01:40.900 --> 01:49.280
That is to say ghosts and miracles and marvelous gadgets of one kind or another.

01:50.120 --> 01:56.860
Why the Odyssey is a science fiction and fantasy saga right there with the witch, Cersei, turning

01:56.860 --> 02:03.780
people into pigs and the monsters, Scylla and Corridus, eating ships and so on.

02:04.920 --> 02:09.800
The transformation of imaginative literature into what we recognize today as science fiction

02:09.800 --> 02:14.600
occurred in the early part of this century, mostly in the pulp magazines such as Hugo

02:14.600 --> 02:16.360
Gernsback's Amazing Stories.

02:16.820 --> 02:21.100
Jack Williamson, who wrote for Gernsback, recalls that there was no term science fiction

02:21.100 --> 02:23.040
when Amazing Stories began in the 20s.

02:24.000 --> 02:28.220
When I started, my first story was printed as science fiction.

02:28.680 --> 02:32.060
Hugo Gernsback wrote the word science and fiction together.

02:32.700 --> 02:37.100
He invited the term science fiction in 29, I think.

02:38.580 --> 02:41.160
And at that time, you had to explain what it was.

02:41.340 --> 02:44.280
I used to say it was the adventure stories with the science background.

02:45.280 --> 02:50.280
This science background was of importance to Gernsback, yet he still wanted stories with

02:50.280 --> 02:51.540
excitement and adventure.

02:52.480 --> 03:00.600
He preached a gospel that science fiction was sugar-coated science, that it was education.

03:01.400 --> 03:09.620
And he got a whole panel of experts with degrees that were supposed to vet the science and

03:09.620 --> 03:13.120
science wonder stories when he started that.

03:13.120 --> 03:21.880
But actually, I think that was as much for him to impress the readers as anything else

03:21.880 --> 03:30.580
because he did use true science in his stories when he could get it, but he also printed

03:30.580 --> 03:32.600
a lot of stories that were pretty wild.

03:33.020 --> 03:38.240
I think always in the magazine, the adventure element was more important than the science.

03:39.260 --> 03:43.920
At first, professional writers didn't contribute much science fiction to the pulps.

03:44.460 --> 03:48.120
The field was new, its readership was uncertain, and the rates were low.

03:49.140 --> 03:51.640
In the beginning, they were amazing.

03:52.880 --> 03:58.660
We filled up with reprints of classic science fiction, and the rates were so low that professional

03:58.660 --> 04:03.320
writers didn't write for them, so they wrote new stories that were mostly written by amateurs

04:03.320 --> 04:04.640
such as myself.

04:04.640 --> 04:10.320
The classic science fiction Williamson mentions was worked by authors who were immensely popular

04:10.320 --> 04:16.700
around the turn of the century and a bit earlier, such as Jules Verne, Edgar Rice Burroughs, and H.G. Wells.

04:17.380 --> 04:21.840
But the new writers did come in a field that has yet had no definition or shape.

04:22.400 --> 04:26.860
These new authors created the styles and themes that are the foundation of today's science fiction.

04:27.260 --> 04:31.880
And most of them, as Williamson recalls, started out in John Campbell's astounding stories.

04:31.880 --> 04:37.280
They all started in Campbell's magazine astounding.

04:38.640 --> 04:57.860
He was, well, I don't know whether you'd say, Campbell discovered them or they discovered him, but it was a small group with a great deal of fellowship or fellow understanding and so forth.

04:57.860 --> 05:02.240
And it was an exciting period and wished to be alive.

