06:43.800 --> 06:44.440
And Darrell Lane.

06:44.920 --> 06:50.180
What we today call science fiction took shape in the pages of the colorful pulp magazines of the 1920s and 30s.

06:50.440 --> 06:54.220
Jack Williamson, who wrote for those pulp magazines, is a living history of science fiction.

06:54.220 --> 06:59.180
His career as a writer goes back to the 1920s before the term science fiction was even created.

06:59.740 --> 07:02.720
He grew up in the early part of this century on the frontier plains of New Mexico.

07:03.200 --> 07:11.780
Not long after he discovered the fresh and exciting new world of science fiction, he began selling his work to Hugo Gernsback's Amazing Stories, which was the first science fiction publication.

07:11.780 --> 07:27.440
I grew up on a sand hill farm in the south part of this county when times were pretty grim and I wanted to be some sort of scientist without any direction.

07:27.900 --> 07:38.040
Means to get a scientific education and a few months after Gernsback started the Old Amazing, I came across some copies of it.

07:38.040 --> 07:50.780
And I was immediately fascinated with experiments that worked with traveling time and spaceships to other worlds and all sorts of wonderful things.

07:51.120 --> 07:54.980
And it's been an important share of my life ever since.

07:56.360 --> 07:58.700
The pay scale for early science fiction writers was minimal.

07:59.200 --> 08:01.360
There were no movie rights or paperback contracts.

08:02.040 --> 08:04.920
Yet Williamson was able to produce enough fiction to make a living at it.

08:05.800 --> 08:15.620
Gernsback paid a half a cent a word or less, which meant, well, you get $25 for a short story and 75 for an hour let.

08:16.340 --> 08:26.120
But Clayton paid two cents a word and up, which is one reason maybe the Clayton magazine went bankrupt and great depression.

08:26.120 --> 08:41.500
But that meant that I could pound out 4,000 words a day for two days and 160 bucks, which was a fabulous feat for a farm kid in depression days.

08:49.580 --> 08:51.420
Amazing stories was a pulp magazine.

08:51.920 --> 08:53.380
A pulp was printed on cheap paper.

08:53.380 --> 08:59.640
There were usually large format magazines with lurid and colorful illustrations on the cover to catch the attention of prospective readers.

09:00.380 --> 09:10.240
In those days, before the paperbacks and before TV and before the comics, my people read a lot more for entertainment than they do nowadays.

09:10.960 --> 09:13.340
And there were really three sorts of magazines.

09:13.340 --> 09:21.520
There were quality magazines like Harper's and The Old Scribner's, The Atlantic for people with brains and the slicks,

09:22.100 --> 09:28.280
printed on coated paper that would take good advertising for people with money to spend.

09:28.600 --> 09:32.520
And the pulp for people who had neither brains nor money.

09:32.880 --> 09:39.020
But we had a lot of fun in the pulp, even if we were looked down upon widely.

09:39.020 --> 09:48.600
And eventually, why science fiction got recognized as being not entirely without brains, let's say.

09:49.040 --> 09:52.280
And nowadays, there's a little bit of money in it sometimes.

09:53.600 --> 09:57.160
A good deal of the early science fiction published in the pulps was space opera.

09:57.780 --> 10:04.900
The term which denotes a melodramatic form of science fiction characterized by heroes and villains, maidens in distress, and intergalactic warfare.

10:04.900 --> 10:06.800
Right, Buck Rogers type stuff.

10:07.180 --> 10:11.580
It's unsophisticated, but Williamson admires it, and he points at it still around in the movies.

10:12.380 --> 10:15.980
I've never objected to space opera. I still think it's wonderful.

10:16.640 --> 10:23.240
And I even think that Star Wars could have been made out of my legend stories, as well as it was from something else.

10:23.260 --> 10:29.040
I enjoyed Star Wars tremendously as a sort of adolescent daydream.

10:29.040 --> 10:36.840
And well, the pulp readers were mostly young and as naive as I was.

10:37.720 --> 10:43.920
And the space opera was a symbolic escape from all sorts of things.

10:50.600 --> 10:58.720
Though it does still turn up now and then, space opera was left behind in science fiction, along with Jack Williamson, moved ahead into its golden age.

