13:01.280 --> 13:04.120
In the late 1930s, science fiction was in transition.

13:04.880 --> 13:09.760
In one sense, it was becoming more sophisticated, outgrowing its early emphasis on space opera.

13:10.280 --> 13:13.420
Jack Williamson, who wrote Space Opera, considers this change natural.

13:14.700 --> 13:25.260
I was growing up and the readers were growing up. That's something that's been going on in science fiction, at least in American science fiction all along.

13:25.260 --> 13:43.860
I think you can draw a distinction between, let's say, European mainstream science fiction on one hand, which has always been recognized and treated as literature and part of American science fiction, which was looked down on.

13:44.260 --> 13:55.240
But as the readers of that grew older, some of them started writing, some of them started editing magazines, most of them outgrew science fiction, but some of them didn't.

13:55.260 --> 14:05.820
So there was a continual increase in the education, the sophistication, and so forth, the whole field.

14:06.660 --> 14:14.160
Among these readers of pulp science fiction were a few who developed into those authors whose work defined what science fiction would become in later years.

14:14.760 --> 14:23.320
These early readers were people like Isaac Asimov, Robert Heinlein, A. E. Van Vogt, Theodore Sturgeon, L. Sprague de Camp, Frederick Poe, and Hal Clement.

14:23.320 --> 14:30.780
And these authors are now the classics, those who wrote in that very special period of science fiction called the Golden Age.

14:31.920 --> 14:39.440
A. E. Van Vogt, looking back at that period, says that he read the authors who were starting out then with him, but that he had no idea they were doing anything special.

14:40.340 --> 14:54.880
Well, I read their stories, you know, I mean, I was always fascinated by these various stories. I read every issue that came out, you know, so when you say what was it like, it just seemed like a perfectly natural thing that was happening.

14:55.680 --> 15:08.480
The notion that we were operating in a special period of time did not occur to me. You know, I mean, we were just doing our thing, and everybody was evidently stimulated in a special way.

15:08.480 --> 15:17.340
Frederick Poe belonged to a group of writers and fans in New York called the Futurians. He remembers the closeness of the group and how they would help each other.

15:18.260 --> 15:25.920
Well, science fiction has some special traits, and one of them is that its readers herd together as much as they can.

15:25.920 --> 15:43.540
They formed fan clubs and associations and corresponded as groups and so on, and in New York City there were quite a few science fiction fans, and about 25 or 30, most of whom wanted to be writers, formed a club called the Futurians.

15:44.280 --> 15:50.960
There were people like Cyril Karnbluth and Isaac Asimov, Damon Knight, and myself, quite a few others.

15:50.960 --> 16:00.220
We did discuss each other's work a lot, and I guess in the process of criticizing it, there was a lot of help given.

16:00.820 --> 16:14.500
I think the biggest factor that made it easier for a lot of us to go on with writing was just the knowledge that other people were doing it, and also the fact that we collaborated a lot.

16:14.500 --> 16:30.700
We remedied each other's deficiencies by writing, I mean by collaborating on single stories, and although most of the stories were not very good, we did learn something by seeing how other people would tackle the same subjects we were writing about.

16:32.020 --> 16:41.500
Elsprague de Camp also remembers this closeness among writers at the beginning of the Golden Age, but like VanVoote, de Camp says that the authors had no sense of participating in anything special.

16:42.240 --> 17:01.780
Well, I daresay that various ones of us did have their greens and fancies at times, and wondered how it was all going to come out, and would this become, would the genre expand and take over the mainstream and various things of that sort.

17:03.880 --> 17:08.940
But as to that mostly, as I said, it was simply a matter of making a living.

17:08.940 --> 17:14.200
But the living those young writers made is the foundation of today's science fiction.

