18:54.420 --> 18:59.040
No individual has left his imprint on modern science fiction as deeply as John W. Campbell.

18:59.660 --> 19:03.660
And he didn't do it as a writer, though he did write good science fiction. He did it as an editor.

19:03.660 --> 19:10.560
Jack Williamson, who wrote for Campbell, speaks of the qualities that made Campbell the most important editor in the history of science fiction.

19:11.680 --> 19:33.220
I think he influenced the way nearly everybody wrote science fiction, because when he became editor of Amazing, and later changed the name to Analog, he had the best highest paying market in the field.

19:33.220 --> 19:45.460
He was, let's say, science fiction was serious to him as a way of speculating about science and its impact on the future of mankind and so forth.

19:46.000 --> 19:52.420
He was tremendously inventive. He was full of ideas that he shared very freely.

19:52.980 --> 20:03.000
And everybody who was writing science fiction for those years was influenced by Campbell, it seems to me, whether directly or not.

20:03.000 --> 20:17.540
If they weren't trying to write for him and reading his letters, they were reading such writers as O. Heinlein and Dick Kamp and Sturgeon and a dozen others who were Kamel writers.

20:18.620 --> 20:22.240
From 1938 to 1950, Campbell edited astounding stories.

20:22.920 --> 20:27.660
1939, his second year as the head of the magazine, was a high point in the history of science fiction.

20:27.660 --> 20:36.680
It was in that year that Campbell published the first science fiction stories of Robert Heinlein, Theodore Sturgeon, A. E. Van Vogt and Isaac Asimov.

20:37.380 --> 20:39.960
Williamson remembers reading their first works in astounding.

20:39.960 --> 20:46.380
They all started in Kamel's magazine astounding.

20:46.660 --> 21:05.740
He was, well, I don't know whether you'd say, Kamel discovered them or they discovered him, but it was, let's say, a small group with a great deal of well-fellowship or fellow understanding and so forth.

21:05.740 --> 21:10.020
It was an exciting period and wished to be alive.

21:10.860 --> 21:14.420
If you were a science fiction fan, it was an exciting period and wished to be alive, all right.

21:14.960 --> 21:22.560
And John Campbell was the right man at the right time, a leader who guided, pushed, and cajoled science fiction into the modern world.

21:23.120 --> 21:29.120
A. E. Van Vogt, one of science fiction's classic authors, recalls that he might not have ever written science fiction, if not for Campbell's encouragement.

21:30.280 --> 21:35.240
I had read science fiction when I was 14 in the early Amazing.

21:38.840 --> 21:49.020
However, it was, the Amazing stories was taken over from Hugo Gernsback by a man called T. O. Connor Sloan, or T. Connor O. Sloan or something like that.

21:49.880 --> 21:55.460
And he didn't know how to edit a magazine and after he'd been editing it for a few issues, I lost interest in.

21:56.500 --> 22:07.600
So I'd never read it again until 1938 when I picked up the issue of the astounding title in which Campbell's own story under a pseudonym was,

22:07.860 --> 22:08.640
Who Goes There?

22:09.600 --> 22:20.100
And when I read that story, I sent him a letter outlining an idea and he answered me.

22:20.100 --> 22:23.540
So if he hadn't answered, I may not have had a science fiction career.

22:24.120 --> 22:27.020
But I'd escalated it, he answered all letters like that.

22:28.440 --> 22:32.620
In addition to encouraging authors, Campbell had helped them locate story ideas.

22:33.020 --> 22:37.760
Frederick Cole, himself an important editor, says this was one of Campbell's greatest strengths as an editor.

22:38.700 --> 22:47.840
Quite a few stories come to be written because an editor says, listen, you've got a notion here that you are throwing away and you really should expand it.

22:47.840 --> 22:50.620
John Campbell was superb at that sort of thing.

22:50.780 --> 22:58.500
Some of the best stories he published were the result of his telling a writer that he had an idea that they didn't realize he had.

22:59.740 --> 23:06.560
John W. Campbell. Science fiction would be here even if he hadn't been, but it surely wouldn't be the same.

