25:12.100 --> 25:18.360
Science fiction owes a debt to John W. Campbell. He brought it into the modern world and had a large hand in initiating its golden age.

25:18.760 --> 25:26.740
During his period as editor of Astounding Stories from 1938 to 1950, Campbell discovered and encouraged writers who are now classics in the field of science fiction.

25:27.220 --> 25:32.040
Author Jack Williamson says that Campbell's influence on an author was not heavy-handed or overly critical.

25:32.580 --> 25:35.940
He was even supportive of ideas he didn't agree with if they happened to be good ones.

25:37.240 --> 25:45.220
Campbell and I thought so much alike, so that I always felt at home with his magazine and enjoyed working with him.

25:46.120 --> 25:57.580
He gave me occasional, very useful suggestions that I used and he never did edit my material,

25:57.740 --> 26:01.360
heavily or tried to persuade me to say anything I didn't want to say.

26:01.900 --> 26:11.680
I believe that personally he was optimistic about science in the future, but when I wrote such a pessimistic, dystopian thing as the folded hands,

26:11.680 --> 26:16.140
he published it as it was and asked for more.

26:17.320 --> 26:19.300
Campbell influenced his authors in different ways.

26:19.780 --> 26:24.580
Elle Sprague de Camp, for instance, remembers him as a teacher, but not as a source of original ideas.

26:25.420 --> 26:29.920
I learned a great deal of what I think I know about storytelling from him.

26:31.420 --> 26:39.580
One thing that did not occur between us was his proposing story ideas and having me write them,

26:39.580 --> 26:45.480
because I've never been very good at turning other people's ideas into effective stories.

26:46.740 --> 26:55.900
So he may have cried it a few times, but when nothing came of it, why, I guess he quit.

26:56.440 --> 27:03.200
I can't think of one story that he proposed and I wrote the story, but then he rejected it.

27:03.200 --> 27:05.640
I finally sold it to one of his competitors.

27:06.140 --> 27:08.560
That was the ghosts of Melvin Pie.

27:09.760 --> 27:16.460
He suggested a ghost story in which the dead man had a split personality, so he had two ghosts.

27:17.680 --> 27:21.500
One thing that Campbell would insist on in stories he bought was scientific accuracy,

27:21.980 --> 27:24.720
the consistency with actual science and the laws of the universe.

27:25.160 --> 27:28.060
Author Howe Clement talks about Campbell's insistence on credibility.

27:28.840 --> 27:32.780
John was the one who bought my first several stories.

27:33.500 --> 27:36.920
I knew him quite well, talked to him quite often.

27:37.280 --> 27:39.020
Well, I didn't always agree with him.

27:39.180 --> 27:43.780
We both felt that there were rules and that they ought to be followed.

27:44.560 --> 27:47.860
We were both materialists, I guess.

27:48.040 --> 27:53.780
We felt that the universe does run by rule and we felt that a story was most believable

27:53.780 --> 28:00.340
when it matched those rules, at least as we mean humanity in general,

28:00.640 --> 28:01.980
currently understood them.

28:02.760 --> 28:06.160
Campbell was involved in publishing Clement's science fiction novel, Mission of Gravity.

28:06.960 --> 28:12.800
Frederick Poe, who was Clement's agent at that time, tells an interesting story regarding the circumstances of its publication.

28:13.420 --> 28:15.720
Poe sent the novel to Campbell, who rejected it.

28:16.660 --> 28:17.420
He sent it back.

28:17.420 --> 28:25.040
He said, pretty good stuff, but you should know, Fred, that there's a difference between a novel that reads well as a book

28:25.040 --> 28:29.040
and a novel that reads well as a serial, and this one just does not break as a serial.

28:30.480 --> 28:34.120
So I knew he was wrong and I knew I couldn't argue him out of it.

28:35.020 --> 28:41.280
And so I looked at the manuscript, which was, I think, 270 pages long or something like that.

28:41.280 --> 28:46.720
And I counted up to page 90 and drew a line under a paragraph there.

28:46.940 --> 28:54.640
I counted up to page 180 and drew a line under a paragraph there and had my secretary retype a couple of pages on each side of each line,

28:55.240 --> 29:01.040
saying at the bottom, the first part, end of part one, at the beginning of the second part, beginning of part two.

29:01.960 --> 29:06.060
And I let it sit for a couple of weeks and I sent it back to John and he bought it.

29:07.160 --> 29:11.020
Mission of Gravity, of course, went on to become one of the classic science fiction novels.

29:11.700 --> 29:14.780
And Campbell is remembered as the greatest editor science fiction has ever had.

29:15.540 --> 29:22.900
It is not coincidental that his time at the head of astounding stories, 1938 to 1950, is now called the Golden Age of Science Fiction.

29:29.620 --> 29:35.660
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association,

29:35.940 --> 29:38.840
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

